        services in <span
          class="bg-gradient-to-r from-[#4D47C6] to-[#2FD6CC] bg-clip-text text-transparent"
        >
          New York City</span
        >
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="text-4xl text-slate-800 mt-10">
      Mobile application and landing page design
    </p>
  </main>

  <Image src={hero} alt="hero" class="" aspectRatio="16/9" />

  <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
    <h1 class="">
      Project
      <p class="">Scope</p>
    </h1>
    <article>
      <h2 class="">The Challenge</h2>
      <p class="">
        While there are many options for micro-mobility services, their products
        can have a high barrier of entry (you need to create an account and set
        up payment for each service you’d like to use), they often don’t address
        road-safety concerns (once you access the device, you don’t necessarily
        get guidance on where you’re going and how to get there safely). Every
        app has different use patterns, so it can be confusing to toggle between
        services to understand how they work.
      </p>
      <h2 class="">The Opportunity</h2>
      <p class="">
        Through Unicycle, we wanted to create a service where users of
        micro-mobility devices can more easily see available vehicles in their
        area, and feel more comfortable on the roads.
      </p>
      <h2 class="">My Role</h2>
      <p class="">
        As part of a group project, my contributions were associated with User
        Research, and app interface design.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

